Interface IItem

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IItemHandle
    All Known Subinterfaces:

    public interface IItem
extends IItemHandle
    Common protocol for simple, auditable, and versionable item states alike.

    Item handles and items are passive data objects that are retrieved or created while the client is logged in to a repository. These objects remain valid if the client logs out.

    Item states, the data for an item, can be augmented with additional open-ended data extensions, called state extensions. State extensions are part of the item state and are captured in the item states as they change over time. Components must "opt-in" to allowing state extensions for a given item type in order for an item state to be augmented. A state extension is a key-value pair, where the key is a distinctive string prefixed by the component id identifying which component is responsible for the given state extension. The values are limited to type String which must be non-null string and limited to 250 characters. Specifying the #com.ibm.team.repository.common.IItem.STATE_EXTENSIONS2_PROPERTY property of an item state when fetching an item from the repository retrieves all of its state extensions.

    Since:
    0.5

        Returns:
        true if the item has state, and false otherwise

      • getModifiedBy

        IContributorHandle getModifiedBy()
        Returns the contributor responsible for creating this state of the item.

        A newly-created item may or may not carry the contributor's id. The initial state of an item bears the item id of the contributor that created the item; other states bear the item id of the contributor that made the change that resulted in that state.

        Returns:
        the contributor responsible for the state, or null if unknown

      • modified

        java.util.Date modified()
        Returns the time at which this item state was created.

        A newly-created item may or may not carry the modified property. Moreover, the modified property is only retrieved when history is requested. Clients that want to see these must use allStates(LARGE) in order to get meaningful values that they can depend on.

        Returns:
        the time at which the state was created, or null if unknown

      • isComplete

        boolean isComplete()
        Returns whether this item is complete or partial. A complete item has all of its properties set, whereas a partial item may have some of its properties not set.
        Returns:
        true if the item is complete, and false if this item is partial

      • isWorkingCopy

        boolean isWorkingCopy()
        Returns whether this item state can be modified.

        Items created via the IItemType#createItem() start off as working copies. Items created independently are not working copies. States retrieved from the repository are not working copies. Use getWorkingCopy()to obtain a working copy from a retrieved or independently created item.

        Working copies do not have state ids (IItemHandle.hasStateId() returns false).

        Implementation note: This flag is strictly a property of the in-memory object.

        Returns:
        true if this state is a working copy, and false otherwise

      • getWorkingCopy

        IItem getWorkingCopy()
        Returns a working copy of this state that can be modified. Returns the receiver if it is already a working copy.

        Items created via the IItemType#createItem() start off as working copies. Items created independently are not working copies. States retrieved from the repository are not working copies. This method must be called to obtain a working copy from a retrieved item or a new item that was created independently; the client must not modify states that are not working copies.

        Modifying the value of a property that is currently unset will cause an IllegalStateException to be thrown.

        Returns:
        a working copy; never null
        See Also:
        isWorkingCopy()

      • isRedactedCopy

        boolean isRedactedCopy()
        Returns whether this item is a redacted copy of the state. A redacted copy has has certain sensitive information removed.

        Implementation note: This flag is strictly a property of the in-memory object.

        Returns:
        true if this state is a redacted copy, and false otherwise

      • setRequestedStateId

        void setRequestedStateId(UUID stateId)
        Request a specific stateId when saving a new state of this working copy. For auditable items, the requested stateId must be different from the stateId for all historical states of all auditable items. For simple items, the stateId must be different from the current stateId. If these uniqueness rules are not followed, saving the item will fail with a TeamRepositoryException. If you use UUID.generate() to produce a stateId, you are guaranteed to get a unique one.
        Parameters:
        stateId - requested state id
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if this is not a working copy
